{{otherships|USS Buffalo}} {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=[[Image:USS Buffalo SSN-715.jpg|300px|USS ''Buffalo'' (SSN-715)]] |Ship caption= }} {{Infobox Ship Career |Hide header= |Ship country= |Ship flag={{USN flag}} |Ship name=USS ''Buffalo'' |Ship namesake= |Ship ordered= |Ship awarded= 23 February 1976 |Ship builder= [[Northrop Grumman Newport News|Newport News Shipbuilding]] |Ship original cost= |Ship yard number= |Ship way number= |Ship laid down= 25 January 1980 |Ship launched= 8 May 1982 |Ship sponsor= |Ship christened= |Ship completed= |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned= 5 November 1983 |Ship recommissioned= |Ship decommissioned= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship renamed= |Ship reclassified= |Ship refit= |Ship struck= |Ship reinstated= |Ship homeport=[[Joint_Base_Pearl_Harbor-Hickam|Pearl Harbor, Hawaii]]<ref>{{cite web|title=USS Buffalo Bids Farewell to Guam|url=http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=71428|publisher=US Navy|accessdate=January 11, 2013}}</ref> |Ship identification= |Ship motto= |Ship nickname= |Ship honors= |Ship captured= |Ship status={{Ship in active service}} |Ship notes= |Ship badge= [[File:USS Buffalo SSN-715 Crest.png|150px]] }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class= {{sclass|Los Angeles|submarine}} |Ship type= |Ship tonnage= |Ship displacement= 5,771 tons light, 6,142 tons full, 371 tons dead |Ship length= {{convert|110.3|m|ftin|abbr=on}} |Ship beam= {{convert|10|m|ftin|abbr=on}} |Ship height= |Ship draft= {{convert|9.7|m|ftin|abbr=on}} |Ship depth= |Ship decks= |Ship power= |Ship propulsion=[[S6G reactor|S6G nuclear reactor]] |Ship speed= |Ship range= |Ship endurance= |Ship test depth= |Ship complement=12 officers, 98 men |Ship time to activate= |Ship sensors= |Ship EW= |Ship armament= 4 × 21 in (533 mm) torpedo tubes |Ship armor= |Ship notes= }} |} '''USS ''Buffalo'' (SSN-715)''', a {{sclass|Los Angeles|submarine}}, was the second ship of the [[United States Navy]] to be named for [[Buffalo, New York]] (another {{USS|Buffalo|1813|6}} was named for the [[American Bison|animal]]). The contract to build her was awarded to [[Northrop Grumman Newport News|Newport News Shipbuilding and Dry Dock Company]] in [[Newport News, Virginia]] on 23 February 1976 and her keel was laid down on 25 January 1980. She was [[ship naming and launching|launched]] on 8 May 1982 sponsored by Mrs. Joanne Kemp, and [[ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 5 November 1983, with Commander G. Michael Hewitt in command.
In 1999, ''Buffalo'' was modified to carry a [[Dry Deck Shelter]] (DDS). In 2002, the ''Buffalo'' entered drydock in Pearl Harbor, Hawaii and became the first ship to undergo nuclear refueling in Hawaii. In late November 2005, the DDS was used to launch an underwater glider capable of gathering and storing information to be later transmitted by means of a built-in satellite phone.
On 10 June 2008, ''Buffalo'' visited [[Olongapo City]] in the [[Philippines]], allowing Filipino children to tour her.[http://www.ctf74.navy.mil/imagery/2008/06a.htm]
Per the Annual Report to Congress on Long-Range Planning for Construction of Naval Vessels for FY2013, ''Buffalo'' is scheduled for decommissioning in 2017.[http://www.wired.com/images_blogs/dangerroom/2012/03/navy-shipbuilding-fy2013.pdf]
