{{Other people|James Cecil}}
'''James Cecil, 3rd Earl of Salisbury''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR-cats|KG|PC}} (1648 &ndash; June 1683), known as '''Viscount Cranborne''' from 1660 to 1668, was an [[England|English]] nobleman. 

==Biography==
Salisbury was the son of [[Charles Cecil, Viscount Cranborne]], the son of [[William Cecil, 2nd Earl of Salisbury]]. His mother was Lady Diana Maxwell. He is said to have attended [[St John's College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{acad|id=CCL634J|name=Cecil, James}}</ref> In 1668 he succeeded his grandfather in the earldom. He was invested a [[Privy Council of England|Privy Council]]lor in 1679 and was made a [[Knight of the Garter]] a year later, but was expelled from the Council shortly before his death.

He died in June 1683 and was succeeded in his titles by his son [[James Cecil, 4th Earl of Salisbury|James]].

==Family==
Lord Salisbury married Lady Margaret Manners, daughter of [[John Manners, 8th Earl of Rutland]], in 1661. She bore him a son James and a daughter Lady [[Margaret Cecil]]. 

